04612nam a22007695i 9789814762137DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162016si     fo  d z      eng d  a97898147621377 a10.1355/97898147621372doi  a(DE-B1597)522145  a(OCoLC)1096436806  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG 7aSOC0080002bisacsh1 aTaylor, Robert H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCan Myanmar’s NLD Government Undo the Gordian Knot of Federalism and Ethnicity? /cRobert H. Taylor. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (30 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tFOREWORD -- tCan Myanmar’s NLD Government Undo the Gordian Knot of Federalism and Ethnicity? -- tCan Myanmar’s NLD Government Undo the Gordian Knot of Federalism and Ethnicity? -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDaw Aung San Suu Kyi has said that peace is the first priority of the National League for Democracy (NLD) when it comes to power in April 2016. Both her remarks at the Union Peace Conference in January and the NLD election manifesto point to ethnicity and federalism being linked. This is a position similar to that taken by the outgoing Thein Sein government and the army. Now that the word “federalism” is accepted as useful in the debate over how to establish an end to Myanmar’s persistent civil wars with ethnically designated armed groups, it was hoped that some meeting of minds might take place. But as revealed at the Union Peace Conference, that is yet to have happened. Rather, spokespersons for the ethnic armed groups continue to speak the language of ethnic rights and a federal army, while the government talks about reaching material and administrative agreements and the army insists that there can only be one army. These debates echo the past, going back to the formation of Myanmar in the late 1940s. In order to break the apparently endless debate about federalism, ethnicity, states and divisions in the Union of Myanmar, perhaps a new approach might be considered — taking federalism a step further to the seventy-four district levels of administration. As the ethnically designated armed groups operate in relatively small and localized areas, a solution that squares the circle between ethnicity and territory might have appeal.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBurma—Ethnic relations. 0aBurma—Politics and government. 0aEthnic Studies. 0aEthnicity—Burma. 4aEthnic Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2016z978311070100508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066299308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS eBook Package 2015-2017z978311060667608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPP Plus eBook-Package 2016z978311070101240uhttps://doi.org/10.1355/978981476213740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789814762137423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789814762137.jpg  a978-3-11-060667-6  ISEAS eBook Package 2015-2017c2015d2017  a978-3-11-066299-3  ISEAS Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-070100-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-070101-2  PP Plus eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK